41 (2) An individual taxpayer seeking a tax credit pursuant to this Code section shall apply
42 to the department for preapproval of such tax credit. Such taxpayer shall specify the
43 taxable year for which he or she is seeking a tax credit.
44 (3) Individual taxpayers that properly apply for preapproval of such tax credit following
45 the procedure developed by the department shall be approved on a first-come, first served
46 basis until the aggregate limit for such tax credits is reached for that year.
47 (4) The department shall preapprove tax credits for each preapproval application within
48 30 days and in the received order of submitted applications. Such preapproved tax credits
49 shall be in the amount of $300.00 for each preapproval application.
50 (5) In the event that an individual taxpayer applies for preapproval and the amount of tax
51 credits available for the taxable year are not sufficient to fully fund the tax credits
52 requested, the department shall deny such taxpayer's request and shall not accept any
53 additional preapproval applications from taxpayers for the taxable year.
54 (6) No individual taxpayer shall be preapproved for a tax credit pursuant to this Code
55 section more than once in the lifetime of the taxpayer; provided, however, that nothing
56 in this Code section shall be construed to prevent an individual taxpayer from applying
57 for preapproval more than once.
58 (d)(1) For a tax credit allowed pursuant to this Code section, an individual taxpayer shall
59 maintain receipts for purchases or costs relative to the eligible expenses for three years
60 following the submission of the taxpayer's tax return claiming such tax credit. Such
61 receipts shall be made available upon request for review by the commissioner.
62 (2) No individual taxpayer shall be allowed credits pursuant to this Code section which
63 exceed a total of $300.00 in the lifetime of the taxpayer.
64 (e) In no event shall the total amount of any tax credit under this Code section for a taxable
65 year exceed the taxpayer's income tax liability. No unused tax credit shall be allowed to
66 be carried forward to apply to the taxpayer's succeeding years' tax liability. No such tax
67 credit shall be allowed the taxpayer against prior years' tax liability.
